stomization-Configuration">Configuration</a></li>=20
<li><span class=3D"TOCOutline">2</span> <a href=3D"#JSPUIConfigurationandCu=
stomization-CustomizingtheJSPpages">Customizing the JSP pages</a></li>=20
</ul>=20
</div>=20
<h2 id=3D"JSPUIConfigurationandCustomization-Configuration">Configuration</=
h2>=20
<p>The user will need to refer to the extensive <a href=3D"/display/DSDOC4x=
/Configuration+Reference">WebUI/JSPUI configurations</a> that are contained=
 in JSP Web Interface Settings.</p>=20
<h2 id=3D"JSPUIConfigurationandCustomization-CustomizingtheJSPpages">Custom=
izing the JSP pages</h2>=20
<p>The JSPUI interface is implemented using Java Servlets which handle the =
business logic, and JavaServer Pages (JSPs) which produce the HTML pages se=
nt to an end-user. Since the JSPs are much closer to HTML than Java code, a=
ltering the look and feel of DSpace is relatively easy.</p>=20
<p>To make it even easier, DSpace allows you to 'override' the JSPs include=
d in the source distribution with modified versions, that are stored in a s=
eparate place, so when it comes to updating your site with a new DSpace rel=
ease, your modified versions will not be overwritten. It should be possible=
 to dramatically change the look of DSpace to suit your organization by jus=
t changing the CSS style file and the site 'skin' or 'layout' JSPs in <em>j=
sp/layout</em>; if possible, it is recommended you limit local customizatio=
ns to these files to make future upgrades easier.</p>=20
<p>You can also easily edit the text that appears on each JSP page by editi=
ng the <em>Messages.properties</em> file. However, note that unless you cha=
nge the entry in all of the different language message files, users of othe=
r languages will still see the default text for their language. See <a href=
=3D"/display/DSDOC4x/Application+Layer#ApplicationLayer-internationalizatio=
n">Internationalization</a> in <a href=3D"/display/DSDOC4x/Application+Laye=
r">Application Layer</a>.</p>=20
<p>Note that the data (attributes) passed from an underlying Servlet to the=
 JSP may change between versions, so you may have to modify your customized=
 JSP to deal with the new data.</p>=20
<p>Thus, if possible, it is recommended you limit your changes to the 'layo=
ut' JSPs and the stylesheet.</p>=20
<p>The JSPs are available in one of two places:</p>=20
<ul>=20
<li><em>[dspace-source]/dspace-jspui/dspace-jspui-webapp/src/main/webapp/</=
em> - Only exists if you downloaded the full Source Release of DSpace</li>=
=20
<li><em>[dspace-source]/dspace/target/dspace-[version].dir/webapps/dspace-j=
spui-webapp/</em> - The location where they are copied after first building=
 DSpace.</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>If you wish to modify a particular JSP, place your edited version in the=
 <strong><em>[dspace-source]/dspace/modules/jspui/src/main/webapp/</em></st=
rong> directory (<em>this is the replacement for the pre-1.5 /jsp/local dir=
ectory</em>), with the same path as the original. If they exist, these will=
 be used in preference to the default JSPs. For example:</p>=20
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>=20
<tr>=20
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p> <strong>DSpace default</strong> </p></td>=20
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p> <strong>Locally-modified version</strong> </=
p></td>=20
</tr>=20
<tr>=20
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p> <em>[jsp.dir]/community-list.jsp</em> </p></=
td>=20
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p> <em>[jsp.custom-dir]/dspace/modules/jspui/sr=
c/main/webapp/community-list.jsp</em> </p></td>=20
</tr>=20
<tr>=20
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p> <em>[jsp.dir]/mydspace/main.jsp</em> </p></t=
d>=20
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p> <em>[jsp.custom-dir]/dspace/modules/jspui/sr=
c/main/webapp/mydspace/main.jsp</em> </p></td>=20
</tr>=20
</tbody>
</table>
</div>=20
<p>Heavy use is made of a style sheet, <em>styles.css</em>. If you make edi=
ts, copy the local version to <em>[jsp.custom-dir]/dspace/modules/jspui/src=
/main/webapp/styles.css</em>, and it will be used automatically in preferen=
ce to the default, as described above.</p>=20
<p>Fonts and colors can be easily changed using the stylesheet. The stylesh=
eet is a JSP so that the user's browser version can be detected and the sty=
lesheet tweaked accordingly.</p>=20
<p>The 'layout' of each page, that is, the top and bottom banners and the n=
avigation bar, are determined by the JSPs <em>/layout/header-*.jsp</em> and=
 <em>/layout/footer-*.jsp</em>. You can provide modified versions of these =
(in <em>[jsp.custom-dir]/dspace/modules/jspui/src/main/webapp/layout</em>),=
 or define more styles and apply them to pages by using the &quot;style&quo=
t; attribute of the <em>dspace:layout</em> tag.</p>=20
<ol>=20
<li>Rebuild the DSpace installation package by running the following comman=
d from your <em>[dspace-source]/dspace/</em> directory:=20
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"theme: Confluence; brush: java; gutter: false" style=3D"font-=
size:12px;">mvn package</pre>=20
</div>
</div></li>=20
<li>Update all DSpace webapps to <em>[dspace]/webapps</em> by running the f=
ollowing command from your <em>[dspace-source]/dspace/target/dspace-[versio=
n]-build.dir</em> directory:=20
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"theme: Confluence; brush: java; gutter: false" style=3D"font-=
size:12px;">ant -Dconfig=3D[dspace]/config/dspace.cfg update </pre>=20
</div>
</div></li>=20
<li>Deploy the the new webapps:=20
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"theme: Confluence; brush: java; gutter: false" style=3D"font-=
size:12px;">cp -R /[dspace]/webapps/* /[tomcat]/webapps</pre>=20
</div>
</div></li>=20
<li>Restart Tomcat<br /> When you restart the web server you should see you=
r customized JSPs.</li>=20
</ol>
    </div>
